Section 1. Checking the behavior/ data-generating process of the âAir Quality Index Dataset for Cincinnatiâ

Code 
library(readxl)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(zoo)
library(tsibble)
library(feasts) #to enable autoplots on tsibble
library(fable)
#library(forecast)

#setting up local working directory and loading dataset
setwd('D:/1Spring/BANA 7050 Forecasting')
AQIdata <- as.data.frame(read_excel('AQI Cincinnati 01252023.xlsx',sheet = "AQI"))
AQIdata <- AQIdata[,c('Date','AQI Value')]
colnames(AQIdata) <- c('Date','AQI')

#Creating a tsibble object at monthly granularity
AQIdata2<-AQIdata %>% filter(Date>="2017-01-01" & Date<="2022-12-31") %>%
  mutate(YM = yearmonth(Date,format = "%Y-%m-%d")) %>%
  group_by(YM) %>%
  summarize(value = mean(AQI)) %>% 
  arrange(YM) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = YM)

Using the âAdditiveâ Classical Decomposition as seasonality doesnât seem to vary over time

  • It seems like the Monthly AQI is variance non-stationary as the variance in AQI doesnât change much over time. We will test for it using rolling standard deviation calculation.

  • There is yearly seasonality present in the data with AQI values going up every summer(June,July) and we can see significant values in seasonal trend - ACF plot, therefore we will have to perform seasonal differencing to make it stationary.

  • We will test for mean stationarity using rolling mean calculation and KPSS test.

  • ACF of remainder without any significant lags, indicates trend and seasonal components are able to define data generating process of trend. Here, we notice one significant lag.

  • Additive Classical Decomposition
  • ACF of Trend
  • Seasonality
  • ACF of Remainder
Code 
AQIdata2_decomp <- AQIdata2 %>%
  model(
    classical_decomposition(value,type = 'additive')
  ) %>%
  components()

AQIdata2_decomp %>% autoplot()

Code 
acf(AQIdata2_decomp %>% drop_na() %>% .$trend,lag.max=12,main='')

Code 
acf(AQIdata2_decomp %>% drop_na() %>% .$seasonal,lag.max=12,main='')

Code 
acf(AQIdata2_decomp %>% drop_na() %>% .$random,lag.max=12,main='')

Checking for stationarity using rolling calculations and statistical tests

  1. We do not observe variance stationarity and therefore dont need to transform our time-series using log/ Box-Cox transformation.
Code 
AQIdata2_roll <- AQIdata2 %>%
  mutate(
      value_sd = zoo::rollapply(value,
      FUN = sd, 
      width = 12, 
      fill = NA))

AQIdata2_rollmean <- AQIdata2_roll %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(YM, value)) +
  geom_line(aes(YM, value_sd),color='blue') +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("AQI standard deviation over time (12 month rolling window)") +
  ylab("AQI") +
  xlab("Year Month")

AQIdata2_rollmean

  1. Performing seasonal differencing for our monthly data by taking 12 month lag difference \[Z_{T} - Z_{t-12}\]
Code 
# performing seasonal differencing 
AQIdata2 <- AQIdata2 %>% mutate(value_sdiff = value - lag(value,n = 12))

3(i). We do not observe mean stationarity and therefore donât need to take first lag difference

Code 
AQIdata2_roll <- AQIdata2 %>%
  mutate(
    value_mean = zoo::rollmean(
      value_sdiff, 
      k = 12, 
      fill = NA))

AQIdata2_rollmean <- AQIdata2_roll %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(YM, value_sdiff)) +
  geom_line(aes(YM, value_mean),color='blue') +
  theme_bw() +
  ggtitle("AQI mean over time (12 month rolling window)") +
  ylab("AQI") +
  xlab("Year Month")

AQIdata2_rollmean

3 (ii). KPSS test confirms it is mean stationary as p value is greater than 0.05

Section 2. Checking ACF/PACF of the transformed time series

The time series appears to be an autoregressive process of order 2 as ACF plot is gradually decreasing and PACF plot has 2 significant lags, therefore we suspect the time-series to be of the order ARIMA(p,d,q) = (2,0,0).

The seasonal component - D is 1 as we have taken one difference to remove seasonality, the seasonal autoregressive and seasonal MA would be 0.

  • ACF of transformed AQI
  • PACF of transformed AQI
Code 
acf(AQIdata2 %>% drop_na() %>% .$value_sdiff,lag.max=12,main='')

Code 
pacf(AQIdata2 %>% drop_na() %>% .$value_sdiff,lag.max=12,main='')

Section 3. Selecting best ARIMA model according to BIC

Best model is ARIMA(2,0,0)+(0,1,0) according to BIC

Code 
# Order = p,d,q (AR, I, MA)
models_bic = AQIdata2 %>%
  model(
    mod1 = ARIMA(value~pdq(1,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod2 = ARIMA(value~pdq(1,1,1)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod3 = ARIMA(value~pdq(1,1,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod4 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,1,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod5 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,1,1)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod6 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod7 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,0)+PDQ(0,0,0)),
    mod8 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,1,0)+PDQ(0,0,0)),
    mod9 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,1)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod10 = ARIMA(value~pdq(3,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0))
    )


models_bic%>%
  glance() %>%
  arrange(BIC)

The in-sample predicted value tends to follow the original time series trend with difference in scale

Code 
best_mod = AQIdata2 %>%
  model(ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0),approximation = F, stepwise = F))

# Get fitted values
fitted = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  .$.fitted

ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(AQIdata2$YM, AQIdata2$value)) +
  geom_line(aes(AQIdata2$YM, fitted), color = "blue", alpha = 0.4) +
  theme_bw() +
  xlab("Year-Month") +
  ylab("AQI")

Section 4. Analyze the residuals

(i). The residual ACF plot indicates there is a significant residual lag present and its not white noise.

Code 
best_mod %>%
  gg_tsresiduals()

(ii). We can use the âLjung-Box Test for Residual Autocorrelationâ to check if there is significant autocorrelation left in the residuals at a particular lag.

Ljung-Box test indicates that lag 1 still has residual auto-correlation as p-value < 0.05

Code 
lag1 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 1, dof = 1)

lag2 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 2, dof = 1)

lag3 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 3, dof = 1)

lag4 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 4, dof = 1)

lag5 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 5, dof = 1)
Code 
table_resid <- data.frame(lag = c(1,2,3,4,5),
                          lb_stat = c(lag1$lb_stat,lag2$lb_stat,lag3$lb_stat,lag4$lb_stat,lag5$lb_stat),
                          pvalue = c(lag1$lb_pvalue,lag2$lb_pvalue,lag3$lb_pvalue,lag4$lb_pvalue,lag5$lb_pvalue))

print(table_resid)
  lag     lb_stat    pvalue
1   1 0.006686352 0.0000000
2   2 0.015012555 0.9024827
3   3 0.021559323 0.9892782
4   4 0.717363647 0.8691124
5   5 1.275724070 0.8654806

As we still see some residual autocorrelation, In order to predict future values, we have now used automated ARIMA tool on the original AQI to find the best model.

Note: We are using original AQI values as we have not performed log/box-cox transformation as it was variance stationary, we will have to apply log/box-cox function as this is not handled by ARIMA internally. Taking lag difference for handling mean stationarity and seasonal difference for handling seasonality is usually handled by âdâ and âDâ terms in ARIMA.

Code 
best_model2 = AQIdata2 %>%
  model(
    fable::ARIMA(value,approximation=F,
    stepwise=F)
  )

best_model2%>% 
  report()
Series: value 
Model: ARIMA(1,0,1)(1,1,0)[12] 

Coefficients:
          ar1     ma1     sar1
      -0.6521  0.9506  -0.5798
s.e.   0.1324  0.0760   0.1099

sigma^2 estimated as 29.36:  log likelihood=-188.19
AIC=384.39   AICc=385.12   BIC=392.77

The output above suggests that ARIMA(1,0,1) with seasonal components(1, 1, 0) is the best fit model. This means that our time series has an auto-regressive and a moving average process. Also, it has a seasonal component as well.

The residual ACF plot doesnât show any significant lags using this model.

Code 
best_model2 %>%
  gg_tsresiduals()

The in-sample predicted value tends to follow the original time series trend pretty well with minor difference in scale

Code 
# Get fitted values
fit2 = best_model2 %>%
  augment() %>%
  .$.fitted

ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(AQIdata2$YM, AQIdata2$value)) +
  geom_line(aes(AQIdata2$YM, fit2), color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
  xlab("Year-Month") +
  ylab("AQI")

The 6-time period forecast:

Code 
best_model2 %>% 
  forecast(h=6) %>%
   autoplot(AQIdata2 %>% bind_rows())+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title = "Forecast using best ARIMA model",
       y = "AQI",
       x = "Year-Month")

#### Section 1. Checking the behavior/ data-generating process of the "Air Quality Index Dataset for Cincinnati"

```{r}
#| label: Loading Packages and Datasets
#| echo: true
#| warning: false
library(readxl)
library(tidyverse)
library(lubridate)
library(ggplot2)
library(zoo)
library(tsibble)
library(feasts) #to enable autoplots on tsibble
library(fable)
#library(forecast)

#setting up local working directory and loading dataset
setwd('D:/1Spring/BANA 7050 Forecasting')
AQIdata <- as.data.frame(read_excel('AQI Cincinnati 01252023.xlsx',sheet = "AQI"))
AQIdata <- AQIdata[,c('Date','AQI Value')]
colnames(AQIdata) <- c('Date','AQI')

#Creating a tsibble object at monthly granularity
AQIdata2<-AQIdata %>% filter(Date>="2017-01-01" & Date<="2022-12-31") %>%
  mutate(YM = yearmonth(Date,format = "%Y-%m-%d")) %>%
  group_by(YM) %>%
  summarize(value = mean(AQI)) %>% 
  arrange(YM) %>%
  as_tsibble(index = YM)
```

### Using the 'Additive' Classical Decomposition as seasonality doesn't seem to vary over time

- It seems like the Monthly AQI is variance non-stationary as the variance in AQI doesn't change much over time. We will test for it using rolling standard deviation calculation.

- There is yearly seasonality present in the data with AQI values going up every summer(June,July) and we can see significant values in seasonal trend - ACF plot, therefore we will have to perform seasonal differencing to make it stationary.

- We will test for mean stationarity using rolling mean calculation and KPSS test.

- ACF of remainder without any significant lags, indicates trend and seasonal components are able to define data generating process of trend. Here, we notice one significant lag.

::: panel-tabset

### Additive Classical Decomposition

```{r,warning=FALSE}
AQIdata2_decomp <- AQIdata2 %>%
  model(
    classical_decomposition(value,type = 'additive')
  ) %>%
  components()

AQIdata2_decomp %>% autoplot()
```

$$Z_{T} - Z_{t-12}$$

# performing seasonal differencing

#### Section 3. Selecting best ARIMA model according to BIC

Best model is ARIMA(2,0,0)+(0,1,0) according to BIC

```{r}
# Order = p,d,q (AR, I, MA)
models_bic = AQIdata2 %>%
  model(
    mod1 = ARIMA(value~pdq(1,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod2 = ARIMA(value~pdq(1,1,1)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod3 = ARIMA(value~pdq(1,1,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod4 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,1,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod5 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,1,1)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod6 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod7 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,0)+PDQ(0,0,0)),
    mod8 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,1,0)+PDQ(0,0,0)),
    mod9 = ARIMA(value~pdq(2,0,1)+PDQ(0,1,0)),
    mod10 = ARIMA(value~pdq(3,0,0)+PDQ(0,1,0))
    )


models_bic%>%
  glance() %>%
  arrange(BIC)
```

The in-sample predicted value tends to follow the original time series trend with difference in scale

best_mod = AQIdata2 %>%

#### Section 4. Analyze the residuals

(i). The residual ACF plot indicates there is a significant residual lag present and its not white noise.

```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
best_mod %>%
  gg_tsresiduals()
```

(ii). We can use the "Ljung-Box Test for Residual Autocorrelation" to check if there is significant autocorrelation left in the residuals at a particular lag.

Ljung-Box test indicates that lag 1 still has residual auto-correlation as p-value < 0.05

```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
lag1 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 1, dof = 1)

lag2 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 2, dof = 1)

lag3 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 3, dof = 1)

lag4 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 4, dof = 1)

lag5 = best_mod %>%
  augment() %>%
  features(.innov, ljung_box, lag = 5, dof = 1)
```

```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
table_resid <- data.frame(lag = c(1,2,3,4,5),
                          lb_stat = c(lag1$lb_stat,lag2$lb_stat,lag3$lb_stat,lag4$lb_stat,lag5$lb_stat),
                          pvalue = c(lag1$lb_pvalue,lag2$lb_pvalue,lag3$lb_pvalue,lag4$lb_pvalue,lag5$lb_pvalue))

print(table_resid)
```

As we still see some residual autocorrelation, In order to predict future values, we have now used automated ARIMA tool on the original AQI to find the best model.

Note: We are using original AQI values as we have not performed log/box-cox transformation as it was variance stationary, we will have to apply log/box-cox function as this is not handled by ARIMA internally. Taking lag difference for handling mean stationarity and seasonal difference for handling seasonality is usually handled by 'd' and 'D' terms in ARIMA.

```{r}
best_model2 = AQIdata2 %>%
  model(
    fable::ARIMA(value,approximation=F,
    stepwise=F)
  )

best_model2%>% 
  report()
```
The output above suggests that ARIMA(1,0,1) with seasonal components(1, 1, 0) is the best fit model. This means that our time series has an auto-regressive and a moving average process. Also, it has a seasonal component as well.

The residual ACF plot doesn't show any significant lags using this model.

```{r}
best_model2 %>%
  gg_tsresiduals()
```

The in-sample predicted value tends to follow the original time series trend pretty well with minor difference in scale

```{r message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
# Get fitted values
fit2 = best_model2 %>%
  augment() %>%
  .$.fitted

ggplot() +

```
